body: The root cause is your keras model is in NHWC, while onnx only support NCHW in conv, so if you open the onnx model, you will find there is a lot of transpose inserted, which result very bad performance. Our converter has some optimization for that but unfortunately we can't eliminate all the transposes...  do you set your keras to channel_first format and train it again?
My understanding is that those optimizations are not in the Keras converter. @wenbingl.

Nathan and I discussed to create a ONNX to ONNX optimization tool a couple weeks agon. We can put common optimizers (e.g., tranpose optimizers, const folder, back to back reshape optimization and etc.) to this tool. All converters call it after finishing converting. And it can also be a standalone tool.  @nathan-yan

ONNX itself has a similar ONNX to ONNX optimization tool (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/PythonAPIOverview.md#optimizing-an-onnx-model ). Is there any plan to combine the optimizations in onnxruntime with those in onnx into one uniform framework?
We prefer not to make Lotus depend on these ONNX optimization. But, we do want to implement some in Lotus if they are really valuable.
@souptc thanks for the root cause, actually what i was expecting is able to use same model for both CPU and GPU runtimes, optimization during runtime will be very helpful!

@SherL0cked , based on the comment above, we already have some optimization in tensorflow converter. a quick trick you can try is to export the keras model's underline tf model, then convert it with TF converter.

I made a change in tf converter, allowing users to load an existing onnx file and call the optimizer directly. Feel free to have a try on that. Simple usage:

https://github.com/onnx/tensorflow-onnx/blob/ff36c8eb446af935c3c07bcf0fd9110a863e66bb/tests/test_optimizers.py#L26 

It's just one line, besides loading the onnx file.
 `new_proto = GraphUtil.opt_transposes_with_model_proto(origin_proto) `

For Keras converter, it should be pretty easy to integrate this tool since it already has dependency on tf-onnx converter. Feel free if you feel good.
@SherL0cked The Keras converter (https://github.com/onnx/keras-onnx) now has the optimizer...can you try your model to see if this issue is resolved?

@faxu I believe this solved issue!
Appreciate all for the efforts.
